 EMMANUEL SAMUEL, YOLA The Nigerian Customs Adamawa/Taraba Command has so far generated the sum of N105,945,138:44k as part of their 2019 revenue generation from January this year to July 2019 respectively. This amount represents 44.66% over last year’s generation of (N73.23M) while this year’s revenue target of (N86.72M) has already been supper seeded. The Controller of Customs Adamawa/Taraba Area Command, Comptroller Kamardeen Olumoh disclosed this while briefing news men on his 2019 achievements at the Customs Area Command Headquarters Yola, Tuesday. The Area Command boss, said, “We witnessed a significant progress in revenue generation from January to July 2019 by generating the sum of N105,945,138.44k only, thereby impacting positively on the morale of officers and men”. According to Olumoh, “This figure represents a 44.66% increase over the corresponding period of the previous year by (N73.23m). When assessed in relation to the revenue target of N86.72m given to the Command for same period, it still marked an increase of 22.17%. So far, the Command has at the end of July, 2019 achieved 71.26% of its annual target”. He explained that the increase in revenue generation was not unconnected with the efforts in Stake Holder sensitization that has encouraged traders to come forward to make proper declaration of their imported items, mostly agricultural produce. “The introduction of NICIS i.e Nigeria Integrated Customs Information System in April/May this year is playing a major role in encouraging importers to make declarations because of its flexibility, which is in tune with the Federal Government Policy on the Ease of doing business” he concluded. Commenting on Anti-smuggling, Karmadeen said the Command has stepped up its anti smuggling war which has led to several seizures. He disclosed that two thousand, five hundred and twenty seven (2,527 x 50kg) of foreign parboiled rice, twelve (12) motor vehicles, twenty two (22) motor cycles, and two hundred and forty (240) bales of second hand clothing were seized. Others seized items include Cartons of Spaghetti, Elephant tusks, Buffalo Horns, used tyres and tricycles. The most recent being the seizure of fifty two (52) drums of petroleum product (PMS) with each drum containing two hundred and thirty litres (230ltrs.), totaling eleven thousand, nine hundred and sixty litres (11,960ltrs.). Karmadeen also disclosed that the Duty Paid Value for all items seized is eighty million, five hundred and ninety eight thousand, four hundred and seventy six naira, twenty three kobo(N80,598,476.23). 